            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being thirteen, sitting at the kitchen table. His father, with a blueprint, was patiently explaining the logic of a load-bearing wall. At the same time, his mother was on the phone, her voice a soft murmur, consoling a neighbor whose cat had died. Adam found himself watching not his parents, but the subtle shift in his father\u2019s posture versus the deep empathy in his mother's tone. In that quiet moment of contrast, he realized he was more interested in the architecture of human feeling than of buildings.\n\n2.\nIt was a Tuesday night at the crisis center, and a sixteen-year-old girl sat across from him, drenched from the rain, refusing to speak. Instead of pushing, Adam just sat with her in the sterile room for nearly an hour, a silent, steady presence. Finally, she whispered, \u201cNo one ever just sits.\u201d The weight and relief in those five words struck him with the force of a physical blow. He wasn't fixing a problem; he was sharing a burden. That night, engineering became a ghost. He was 19.\n\n3.\nHis first year in San Francisco, overwhelmed and broke during his Master's program, he felt swallowed by the city's indifference. After a brutal day of fieldwork, he wandered down Clement Street. The scent of garlic noodles and roasted duck filled the air. He spent his last ten dollars on a steaming bowl of pho at a crowded, brightly-lit restaurant. Surrounded by the chatter of families, the warmth of the broth grounded him. It wasn't just food; it was a promise of belonging. The city, for the first time, felt like home.\n\n4.\nFive years ago, he lost a student he\u2019d been counseling for months\u2014a bright, withdrawn boy who had just started opening up. The news of his relapse felt like a personal failure. Adam carries the memory not of the phone call, but of the empty chair in his office the following week, a void where progress used to be. The lingering ache of that absence is what fuels his dream for his own practice\u2014a place with more time, more resources, and fewer empty chairs.\n\n5.\nLast winter, after a day spent mediating a bitter custody dispute that left a child in tears, he couldn't face his quiet apartment. He went for a run. The cold fog in Golden Gate Park was so thick he could barely see the path ahead. He just ran, his breath ragged, his legs burning, until the physical exhaustion quieted the noise in his head. The run didn\u2019t solve anything, but it was a reminder: to endure the storm, sometimes you just have to move through it, one step at a time."
